GEO 348 Final Project: Chicago COVID-19 Vaccinations¶

Danyah Khan¶

The covid-19 pandemic continues to affect the global population. It has had signicant economic and societal impacts and has affected all aspects of life. Common preventive measures that have been taken include social distancing, lockdowns, quarantines, travel restrictions, face mask mandates, self-isolation. So, becoming vaccinated has become increasingly imporant. The covid-19 vaccines (pfizer, moderna, astraZeneca, etc.) decrease the risk of contracting covid-19 and protects individuals as well as anyone they are in contact with.

Reciving the vaccine has importance in other areas of life. This can include traveling to different coutries where a covid-19 vaccine is required or a negative covid-19 test. Universities throughout the U.S. also require students to be vaccinated before coming to in person classes. One example of this is DePaul Univesity, where we as students must upload the vaccination card in order to be on campus for the 2021-22 academic year.

There are a number of reasons that prevent people from getting vaccinated. In the article, "The 6 reasons Americans arent getting vaccinated", the author highlights a number of reasons why people in America are not getting vaccinated. These reasons include: lack of access to vaccines, a refusal to see Covid-19 as a threat, concern about the vaccines side effects, little trust in the vaccines or the institutions behind them, and belief in at least one of several different conspiracy theories.

The pandemic has raised underlying issues of health equity, racial discrimination, geographic discrimination, etc. The purpose of this project is to learn more about the socio-economic disparities throughout Chicago as well as examinig the covid-19 vaccination completion rates as they differ by zip code areas in Chicago. This will provide an insight on how vaccination completions differ by these different areas.

Article link: https://www.vox.com/2021/6/2/22463223/covid-19-vaccine-hesitancy-reasons-why

import numpy as np

Geospatial data¶

The covid-19 vaccination completion rate contains data as of May 2021. The following variables are being examined: Economic Diversity Index. Uninsured residents, rate of residents uninsured, median house income, college graduation rate, poverty rate, unemployment rate, covid cases, covid case rate, and covid vaccination completetion rate. All of the variables, except for the covid-19 related attributes, are collected from 2015-2019.

The data is availale from the Chicago Health Atlas. https://chicagohealthatlas.org/download. The zipcode data in Chicago is used because there is no available covid data for census tracts and community areas. This resulted in fewer data points.

The shapefile used to join the dataset on the similar attributes can be found from Data.gov. https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/tiger-line-shapefile-2019-2010-nation-u-s-2010-census-5-digit-zip-code-tabulation-area-zcta5-na

This plot shows that as the economic diversity index increases, the covid vaccination completion rate decreases. This aligns with the -0.81 correlation value. Economic diversity measures how much an area has a mix of economic activities. It would be interesting to learn more about the reason for the low vaccination rate if it has any relation to EDI.

Boxplot and Violinplot¶

In [33]:
vaxRates.boxplot(figsize=(16,6))
Out[33]:
<AxesSubplot:>
In [34]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(18, 12))
sns.violinplot(figsize=(16,6), data = vaxRates)
Out[34]:
<AxesSubplot:>

The boxplot and violin plot give a general idea of what the range of the different rate variables look like. The uninsured rate of residents have a high concentration of values that range from 0%-18%. The college grade rate varies roughly equally from 0 to 100 percent. The poverty rate heavily ranges from 0 to 30 percent. The unemployment rate is highly concentrated from 0 to 15%. The covid vaccination completion rate ranges more highly from 20 to 60%.

Determing whether there are statistically signicant spatial clusters/outliers with the covid-19 vaccination rates.¶

In [73]:
# 'HH' if quadrant type is 1 
# 'LH' if quadrant type is 2
# 'LH' if quadrant type is 3
# 'LH' if quadrant type is 4 
cond_hh = (gdfLM['LMQ_vaxRate'] == 1) & (gdfLM['LMP_vaxRate'] <= 0.05)
cond_lh = (gdfLM['LMQ_vaxRate'] == 2) & (gdfLM['LMP_vaxRate'] <= 0.05)
cond_ll = (gdfLM['LMQ_vaxRate'] == 3) & (gdfLM['LMP_vaxRate'] <= 0.05)
cond_hl = (gdfLM['LMQ_vaxRate'] == 4) & (gdfLM['LMP_vaxRate'] <= 0.05)

gdfLM.loc[cond_hh,'LISA_Type'] = 'HH'
gdfLM.loc[cond_lh,'LISA_Type'] = 'LH'
gdfLM.loc[cond_ll,'LISA_Type'] = 'LL'
gdfLM.loc[cond_hl,'LISA_Type'] = 'HL'

# create a countplot to show where it falls into the quadtrant type
sns.countplot(x='LISA_Type',data=gdfLM)

In [77]:
m = folium.Map(location=[mc_y,mc_x],zoom_start=10,tiles='cartodbpositron')

# set color palette for LL, HL, LH
lmq_c = {'LL':'blue','HL':'orange','LH':'lightskyblue'}

def style_function(feature):
    
    lmq_type = lisa_series.get(feature['properties']['FIPS'],None)
    if lmq_type is None:
        return {'fillOpacity':0.5, 'weight':0.5, 'fillColor':'gray', 'color':'white'}
    else:
        return {'fillOpacity':0.5, 'weight':0.5, 'fillColor':lmq_c[lmq_type], 'color':'white'}
    

tt = folium.GeoJsonTooltip(fields=['FIPS','covidvaxCompletionRate','LISA_Type'])

folium.GeoJson(gdfLM,style_function=style_function, tooltip=tt).add_to(m)
                                   
m

With the interactive map, we can visualize where the 4 statistically significant spatial clusters/outliers are located for the covid vaccination completion rate.

It would be interesting to see how this changes with a different type of data, like the census tracts, which has more available points. However, the covid vaccination data was only available for the zipcodes on the Chicago health atlas website.

Discussion¶

There are clear differences in unemployment rates, income levels, graduation rate, that differ between different areas in Chicago by the zipcode. The covid-19 vaccination completion rate also has significant differences between areas The spatial weights of this also shows a more detailed look into how the different socioeconomic factors differ in Chicago.

In the future, it would be interesting to see the vaccination sites in Chicago and how that looks with the different socioeconomic factors that were examined in this project. Additionally, if there is data that becomes available on the Chicago health atlas website that includes the covid data, there would be a lot more data points available from the census tracts or community areas.
